pipeline {
    agent any

    parameters {
        choice(
            name: 'APP_VERSION',
            choices: ['v1', 'v2'],
            description: 'Select Retail Store application version'
        )
    }

    environment {
        AWS_REGION   = 'ap-southeast-2'
        CLUSTER_NAME = 'retail-dev-eksdemo1'
        NAMESPACE    = 'retailstore'
    }

    stages {

        stage('Clean Workspace') {
            steps {
                deleteDir()
            }
        }

        stage('Checkout Code') {
            steps {
                checkout scm
            }
        }

        stage('Set Helm Chart Path') {
            steps {
                script {
                    if (params.APP_VERSION == 'v1') {
                        env.HELM_DIR = "03_RetailStore_Helm_with_Data_Plane/01_retailstore_charts_updates/charts_v1.0.0"
                    } else {
                        env.HELM_DIR = "03_RetailStore_Helm_with_Data_Plane/01_retailstore_charts_updates/charts_v2.0.0"
                    }

                    echo "Selected Version : ${params.APP_VERSION}"
                    echo "Helm Directory   : ${env.HELM_DIR}"
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Configure Kubeconfig') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                mkdir -p ~/.kube

                aws eks update-kubeconfig \
                    --region ${AWS_REGION} \
                    --name ${CLUSTER_NAME}
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Verify Cluster') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                kubectl get nodes
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy Retail Store') {
            steps {
                dir("${HELM_DIR}") {
                    sh '''
                    set -e

                    echo "Deploying Retail Store ${APP_VERSION}"

                    for chart in */ ; do

                        APP=$(basename "$chart")

                        echo "------------------------------------------"
                        echo "Deploying $APP"
                        echo "------------------------------------------"

                        helm upgrade --install "$APP" "$chart" \
                            --namespace ${NAMESPACE} \
                            --create-namespace \
                            --wait

                        echo "$APP deployment completed"

                    done
                    '''
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy Ingress') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                kubectl apply -f 03_RetailStore_Helm_with_Data_Plane/kubernetes/retail-ingress.yaml
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Verify Deployment') {
            steps {
                sh '''
                echo "========== Helm Releases =========="
                helm list -n ${NAMESPACE}

                echo ""

                echo "========== Pods =========="
                kubectl get pods -n ${NAMESPACE}

                echo ""

                echo "========== Services =========="
                kubectl get svc -n ${NAMESPACE}

                echo ""

                echo "========== Deployments =========="
                kubectl get deploy -n ${NAMESPACE}
                '''
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        success {
            echo "Retail Store ${params.APP_VERSION} deployed successfully."
        }

        failure {
            echo "Retail Store deployment failed."
        }
    }
} , i want to delete the objects created by this script
Copilot said
To delete the Kubernetes objects created by your Jenkins pipeline, you’ll essentially need to reverse the Helm and kubectl apply actions. Here’s how you can structure a cleanup stage in your pipeline:

groovy


Copy
stage('Cleanup Retail Store') {
    steps {
        script {
            echo "Cleaning up Retail Store ${params.APP_VERSION}"

            // Delete Helm releases
            sh '''
            set -e

            echo "========== Deleting Helm Releases =========="
            helm list -n ${NAMESPACE} -q | xargs -r -n1 helm uninstall -n ${NAMESPACE}

            echo "========== Deleting Ingress =========="
            kubectl delete -f 03_RetailStore_Helm_with_Data_Plane/kubernetes/retail-ingress.yaml --ignore-not-found

            echo "========== Deleting Namespace =========="
            kubectl delete namespace ${NAMESPACE} --ignore-not-found
            '''
        }
    }
}
🔑 Explanation
helm uninstall: Removes all Helm releases deployed in the namespace.

kubectl delete -f: Deletes the ingress resource applied earlier.

kubectl delete namespace: Cleans up the entire namespace, removing all objects inside it.

--ignore-not-found: Ensures the pipeline doesn’t fail if the resource is already gone.

⚠️ Notes
If you want to preserve the namespace but only remove the apps, skip the kubectl delete namespace line.

If you deployed other resources outside Helm (like ConfigMaps or Secrets), you may need explicit kubectl delete commands for them.

Always run cleanup in a controlled environment (dev/test) before applying in production.

Would you like me to adjust this cleanup so it only removes Helm releases and ingress, but keeps the namespace intact for future deployments?







